'''Heinz Faßmann''' (born August 13, 1955 in [[Düsseldorf]]) is an [[Austria]]n politician and [[professor]] of [[human geography]] and [[land-use planning]] at the [[University of Vienna]]. Since December 2017, Faßmann has been serving as the [[Ministry of Education (Austria)|minister of education]] in the [[Kurz government|Kurz cabinet]]. Faßmann is considered to be aligned with the [[Austrian People's Party]] but holds no formal party membership or affiliation.

== Early life ==

Heinz Faßmann was born on August 13, 1955 in [[Düsseldorf]], [[Germany]].

He spent his childhood and adolescence in [[Vienna]].

Faßmann attended primary school from 1962 to 1966 and [[Gymnasium (school)|gymnasium]] from 1966 to 1974.<ref name="parlcv">{{cite web|url = https://www.parlament.gv.at/WWER/PAD_02975/index.shtml | title = Dr. Heinz Faßmann | website = Austrian Parliament | accessdate = 2018-05-10 }}</ref>

== Career ==

Faßmann studied [[geography]] and [[economic history|social and economic history]] at the [[University of Vienna]], graduating with a [[Doctor of Philosophy|PhD]] in 1980.<ref name="ma">{{cite web | url = https://www.meineabgeordneten.at/Abgeordnete/Heinz.Fassmann | title = Univ.-Prof. Dr. Heinz Faßmann | website = Meine Abgeordneten | accessdate = 2018-05-10 }}</ref>
From 1980 to 1981,<ref name="parlcv"/> he was engaged in postgraduate work in [[sociology]] at the [[Institute for Advanced Studies (Vienna)|Institute for Advanced Studies]].<ref name="unicv">{{cite web | url = https://raumforschung.univie.ac.at/team/fassmann-heinz/ | title = Heinz Faßmann, Univ. Prof. Dr. | website = University of Vienna | accessdate = 2018-05-10 }}</ref>

From 1981 to 1992, Faßmann was a researcher with the [[Austrian Academy of Sciences]]. He spent his academy years on the academy's commission on land-use planning ({{lang|de|Kommission für Raumforschung}}). On the strength of his commission work, he was appointed director of the Institute of City and Regional Planning ({{lang|de|Institut für Stadt- und Regionalforschung}}) in 1992.<ref name="parlcv"/>

Four years later, in 1996, Faßmann left Vienna and the academy to become a C4 professor of human geography and geoinformatics at the [[Technical University of Munich]].
Another four years later, in 2000, Faßmann returned to Vienna to teach human geography and land-use planning at his alma mater. In 2011, he was made the university's [[prorector|vice rector]], a post he held until his transition into politics in 2017.<ref name="parlcv"/>
He also served as a member of the [[Academic Senate|senate]] of the University of Vienna from 2000 to 2006 and as the [[dean (education)|dean]] of the Faculty of Geosciences from 2006 to 2011.<ref name="unicv"/>

In addition to his academic work, Faßmann held positions on various committees and sat on the [[supervisory board]]s of a number of companies, including one [[university spin-off]] incubator.
Faßmann ran a spin-off of his own, the Heinz Faßmann Projektentwicklung KG, from 2013 to 2018.<ref name="ma"/>
He was director of the Expert Commission of German Foundations on Integration and Migration ({{lang|de|Sachverständigenrat deutscher Stiftungen für Integration und Migration}}) from 2009 to 2017.<ref name="rektorcv">{{cite web | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20171216082943/https://rektorat.univie.ac.at/rektorat/vizerektorinnen/vizerektor-fassmann/lebenslauf/ | archivedate = December 16, 2017 | url = https://rektorat.univie.ac.at/rektorat/vizerektorinnen/vizerektor-fassmann/lebenslauf/ | accessdate = 2018-05-10 | title = Vizerektor Faßmann | website = University of Vienna }}</ref>
In 2006 he was, for the second time, appointed Director of the Institute of City and Regional Planning.<ref name="ma"/>

Faßmann routinely acted as a political consultant and advisor to the Austrian government. He became chairman of the [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Austria)|Ministry of Europe, Integration and Foreign Affairs]] Expert Commission on Integration ({{lang|de|Expertenrat für Integration}}) in 2010.<ref>{{cite web | website = Ministry of Foreign Affairs | url = https://www.bmeia.gv.at/integration/expertenrat/ | title = Expertenrat – BMEIA, Außenministerium Österreich | accessdate = 2016-12-15}}</ref>
He has been sitting on the [[Ministry of the Interior (Austria)|Ministry of the Interior]] Migration Council for Austria ({{lang|de|Migrationsrat für Österreich}}),
later renamed Migration Commission ({{lang|de|Migrationskommission}}),<ref>{{cite web | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20171226073901/https://www.oeaw.ac.at/isr/team/direktion/heinz-fassmann/ | archivedate = 2017-12-26 | url = https://www.oeaw.ac.at/isr/team/direktion/heinz-fassmann/ | title = Heinz Fassmann |accessdate = 2018-05-10| website = OEAW}}</ref>
since 2014.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.bmi.gv.at/cms/bmi/_news/bmi.aspx?id=5458593070466150436C303D&view=1 |title = Aktuelles & News | accessdate = 2016-12-15 | website = Ministry of the Interior}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | last = Sterkl | first = Maria | title = Österreich braucht Migration | website = [[Der Standard]] | date = December 15, 2017 | url = http://derstandard.at/2000049319486/Innenminister-Oesterreich-braucht-Migration | accessdate = 2018-05-10}}</ref>

Although Faßmann had never held elected office and never officially attached himself to any political party, he was invited to join the [[Kurz government|Kurz cabinet]] as the [[Ministry of Education (Austria)|minister of education]].
When the cabinet took office on December 18, 2017, Faßmann was appointed [[Ministry of Education (Austria)|minister of education and science]]. Following a reshuffling of ministerial responsibilities − a move regularly made by new parliamentary majority leaders − he became [[Ministry of Education (Austria)|minister of education, science and research]] on January 8, 2018.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://diepresse.com/home/innenpolitik/5349890/Acht-Minister-erneut-angelobt | title = Acht Minister erneut angelobt | website = [[Die Presse]] | date = January 8, 2018 | accessdate = 2018-05-10 }}</ref>
Faßmann has resigned his positions as a vice rector, as the chairman of the commission, and as a member of the council. For the duration of his term in cabinet office, he has also suspended his position as the director of the Institute of City and Regional Planning.

== Personal life ==

Born a German, Heinz Faßmann has been a naturalized Austrian citizen since 1994.

He is married and has two children.

Faßmann stands well over two meters tall. Correcting media reports that erroneously cited even greater numbers, Faßmann states his height at 203&nbsp;cm.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.krone.at/1599090 | date = December 23, 2017 | website = [[Kronen Zeitung]] | title = Minster Faßmann: Übernehmen Sie ein Himmelfahrtskommando? | accessdate = 2018-05-10 }}</ref>

