{{other uses of|Portmanteau|Portmanteau (disambiguation)}}
[[File:Gladstone bag made of ox leather.jpg|thumb|A 16-inch [[Gladstone bag]] made of ox leather]]
A '''portmanteau''' is a piece of luggage, usually made of leather and opening into two equal parts. Some were large, upright, and hinged at the back and enabled hanging up clothes in one half,<ref>http://www.collinsdictionary.com/dictionary/english/portmanteau</ref> while others are much smaller bags (such as [[Gladstone bag]]s) with two equally sized compartments.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.achome.co.uk/antiques/vintage_luggage.htm |title=A History of Vintage Luggage |accessdate=January 16, 2014}}</ref>  The word derives from the French word ''portemanteau'' (from ''porter'', "to carry", and ''manteau'', "coat"),<ref>http://dictionary.reference.com/browse/portmanteau</ref><ref>http://www.answers.com/topic/portmanteau-new-word</ref> which nowadays means a coat rack but was in the past also used to refer to a traveling case or bag for clothes.<ref>[[Petit Robert]]: ''portemanteau'' - "malle penderie" (suitcase in which clothes hang)</ref><ref>[http://www.cnrtl.fr/lexicographie/portemanteau "portemanteau" in le Trésor de la langue française informatisé (The Digitized Treasury of the French Language)] </ref>

